<pretext>
    <article xml:id="notes">
        <worksheet margin="1in" bottom="1.25cm" xml:id="sec-III-3-sols">
        <title><m>\S III.3</m>: Functions From Functions</title>
            <page>
                <exercise workspace=".25in">
                    <title>Motivation: Functions from Functions </title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            We've seen that we can obtain new sets from old sets, new relations from old relations; what are
                            common ways to obtain new functions from old functions?
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                
                </exercise>
                <exercise workspace="6in">
                    <title>Function Arithmetic</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            Let <m>f:\R \to \R</m> and <m>g: \R \to \R</m> be given by <m>f(x)=x^2+x+1</m>
                            and <m>g(x)= 2x</m>.
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            We can combine functions in many of the same ways that we combine numbers.
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        Function addition: 
                                        <me>
                                            (f+g)(x) := f(x) + g(x)= x^2 + 3x +1
                                        </me>
                                        
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        Function subtraction: 
                                        <me>
                                            (g-f)(x) := g(x) - f(x)= 2x - (x^2+x+1)=-x^2+ x-1
                                        </me>
                                        
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        Function multiplication: 
                                        <me>
                                            (f \cdot g)(x) := f(x) \cdot g(x)= 2x^3 + 2x^2 + 2x
                                        </me>
                                        
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        Function division: 
                                        <me>
                                            (f/g)(x) := \frac{f(x)}{g(x)}= \frac{x^2+x+1}{2x}
                                        </me>.
                                        Not that this operation can change the domain.
                                        
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Because functions are relations, we can also perform <term>function composition</term>, as long
                            as the target of the "first" function matches the domain of the "second" function.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            For example, if we first plugged an input into <m>g: \R \to \R</m>, we would get an output in <m>\R</m>.
                            This is also the domain of <m>f: \R \to \R</m>, so we could plug that output into <m>f</m>. This is called
                            <term><m>f</m> composed with <m>g</m></term>:
                            <me>
                                (f \circ g)(x) := f(g(x)) = (2x)^2 + (2x) + 1 = 4x^2 + 2x +1
                            </me>
                            Similarly, we could perform <m>g</m> composed with <m>f</m>:
                            <me>
                                (g \circ f)(x) := g(f(x)) = 2(x^2+x+1) = 2x^2 + 2x + 2
                            </me>
                            Notice that in general, the order of the composition matters, and in some cases, one ordering will make
                            sense while another will not because of target/domain mismatches.
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                </exercise>
            </page>
            <page>
                <exercise workspace="2in">
                    <title>Practice: Function Composition</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            Let <m>k: \R \to \Z</m> and <m>h: \N \to \R</m> be given by <m>k(x)= 2^x + x^3</m>
                            and <m>h(x)= 2+\sqrt{x}</m>. Determine which composition makes sense (<m>k \circ h</m> or <m>h \circ k</m>),
                            then compute it.
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            The composition that makes sense is 
                            <me>
                                (k \circ h)(x) = k(h(x))= 2^{2+\sqrt{x}} + (2+\sqrt{x})^3
                            </me>,
                            which is a function with domain <m>\N</m> and target <m>\R</m>.
                            
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                </exercise>
